  "prompt": "Why hollow shaft can transmit more torque than solid shaft?",
  "response": "A hollow shaft can transmit more torque than a solid shaft of the same outer diameter and material because of its superior **torsional stiffness** and **efficient distribution of material**. Here's why:\n\n### 1. **Better Utilization of Material (Higher Second Moment of Area)**\n   - Torque transmission capability depends on the **polar moment of inertia (\\( J \\))**, which is a measure of a shaft's resistance to torsion.\n   - For a hollow shaft, the material is distributed farther from the central axis, which significantly increases \\( J \\). The formula for the polar moment of inertia of a hollow shaft is:\n     \\[\n     J = \\frac{\\pi}{32} (D_o^4 - D_i^4)\n     \\]\n     where \\( D_o \\) is the outer diameter and \\( D_i \\) is the inner diameter.\n   - Compared to a solid shaft (\\( J = \\frac{\\pi}{32} D_o^4 \\)), the hollow shaft has a higher \\( J \\) for the same outer diameter, making it stronger in torsion.\n\n### 2. **Weight Reduction**\n   - A hollow shaft has less material (weight) than a solid shaft of the same outer diameter. This reduces the overall weight of the system, which is beneficial in applications like aerospace, automotive, and machinery where weight savings are critical.\n\n### 3. **Higher Strength-to-Weight Ratio**\n   - Since the hollow shaft has a higher polar moment of inertia and lower weight, it offers a better **strength-to-weight ratio**. This makes it more efficient in transmitting torque without adding unnecessary mass.\n\n### 4. **Reduced Stress Concentrations**\n   - Hollow shafts distribute stress more evenly across the cross-section. In torsion, the outermost fibers of the shaft experience the highest stress. By removing material from the center (which contributes little to resisting torsion), the hollow shaft minimizes stress concentrations.\n\n### Practical Considerations:\n   - Hollow shafts are commonly used in applications like drive shafts, propeller shafts, and other rotating components where high torque transmission and weight optimization are required.\n   - However, hollow shafts may be more expensive to manufacture and may require additional considerations for mounting and connections compared to solid shafts.\n\n### Conclusion:\nA hollow shaft transmits more torque than a solid shaft because it leverages the material more efficiently, increasing the polar moment of inertia while reducing weight. This makes hollow shafts ideal for high-performance applications where both strength and weight are critical factors.",
